Then $\cos \angle AQC = -\cos \angle CQA,$ so by the Law of Cosines on triangle $AQC,$
\[x^2 = \left( \frac{5}{2} \right)^2 + \left( \frac{3}{2} \right)^2 - 2 \cdot \frac{5}{2} \cdot \frac{3}{2} \cdot \left( -\frac{4}{5} \right) = \frac{49}{4}.\]Then $P$ lies on the circle centered at $Q$ with radius $x.$

Also, $\cos \angle BPD = -\cos \angle DPC,$ so by the Law of Cosines on triangle $BPD,$
\[x^2 = \left( \frac{3}{2} \right)^2 + \left( \frac{5}{2} \right)^2 - 2 \cdot \frac{3}{2} \cdot \frac{5}{2} \cdot \left( -\frac{3}{5} \right) = \frac{49}{4}.\]Then $P$ also lies on the circle centered at $Q$ with radius $x.$  Therefore, $P$ lies at one of the two intersection points of these circles.

