Then $PC = 2x$ and $PB = 2y,$ so by the Law of Cosines on triangles $APC$ and $BPD,$
\begin{align*}
25x^2 &= 16 + 64 - 64 \cdot \frac{4}{5} = 16 + 12 = 28, \\
25y^2 &= 16 + 64 - 64 \cdot \frac{3}{5} = 16 + \frac{192}{5} = \frac{136}{5}.
\end{align*}Since $ABCD$ is a line of length 3, the coordinates of $P$ are of the form $\frac{3}{2} \pm k$ for some $k.$  Then
\[\cos \angle BPC = \frac{(2y)^2 + (2x)^2 - 1^2}{2 \cdot 2y \cdot 2x} = \frac{y^2 + x^2 - \frac{1}{4}}{2xy}.\]By the Law of Cosines on triangle $BPC,$
\begin{align*}
4y^2 + 4x^2 - 8xy \cos \angle BPC &= 1^2, \\
8xy \cos \angle BPC &= 4x^2 + 4y^2 - 1^2, \\
\cos \angle BPC &= \frac{x^2 + y^2 - \frac{1}{4}}{2xy}.
\end{align*}Hence,
\begin{align*}
\sin (2 \angle BPC) &= 2 \sin \angle BPC \cos \angle BPC \\
&= 2 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{1 - \cos^2 \angle BPC}}{\sqrt{1 - \cos^2 \angle BPC}} \cdot \cos \angle BPC \\
&= \boxed{\frac{2 \sqrt{5}}{5}}.
\end{align*}

